{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93a91aea-7b53-4c44-bb95-b0292453b64f","content":"**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (lightweight, .NET-aware, no install beyond the global tool).\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**Alternative for deeper OS-level analysis:** use `PerfView` directly:\n\n```powershell\nPerfView.exe collect /ThreadTime /CircularMB:500 /BufferSizeMB:256\n```\n\nPerfView captures both managed and native stacks and is better for diagnosing thread pool starvation or native interop issues.\n\n**Quick triage tip:** While the trace runs, check hot threads with:\n```powershell\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48d8e5ba-ceb1-4410-8201-135ea3d58216","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a general knowledge question about performance diagnostics — no code changes or repository exploration needed. I'll give a concise answer.","outputTokens":318,"requestId":"CB16:A3554:1D0BF1C:202CAFC:6A05252C"},"id":"27f250c9-de35-4242-8400-a52195d23686","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:28:23.201Z","parentId":"a8708c8e-43dd-4fa3-99f7-a995163bf37c"}
